segments.text: So that our graduates tend to have a sort of common point of view, regardless of their specialization.
Then they will, then of course, within their specialization, they will have the point of view that they pick up from those faculty members.
I think we have been working very hard to encourage them to stand on our shoulders,
to exceed what we have been able to think and accomplish.

I think that more and more members of this department are involving doctoral students in research activities and co-publishing activities so that they finish their degrees with three or four publications already on the books.
It's not universal, but it's expanding.
The very nature of this department is that it is diverse.
The people that we hire have some kind of specialization.
There are very few of us that are generic.
I'm going to put it that way.
I'm on one hand and have fingers left over.
Otherwise, they're English educators or they're reading specialists or they're math educators or they're elementary educators or middle school people or something.
They've got some sort of specialization.
And they tend to focus on teaching courses and working programs that
that take advantage of their specialization.
So the generalists are kind of the amalgam that holds it all together, if you will.
And if the three or four or five of us
cast our votes all together with one cluster or another cluster, we can have a majority, if you will.
We don't really have that political in the way we go at it.
It's much more a matter of conscience.
But still, the net result of that interaction, interplay between the specialization and the general has been a rather unique kind of
situation.
There's diversity within commonality or something.
And is there a pretty good degree of freedom to express that diversity and that uniqueness?
Yes, yes, yes.
I think there always has been.
Certainly, when Johnson there was, and I was department head, I encouraged it.
Where were you department head?
What years?
Oh, dear.
Well, I'm sure it's in the...
I was roughly...
You were between Johnson and, has there been three, just Johnson and you and Dr. Peters?
Well, David David was interim department head for one year.
Okay.
Okay.
And he's serving in that capacity.
I mean, he's interim department head right now in IVT.
Okay.
Now that we've talked about the department and the college and everything else, can we talk just for a few final moments on Robert Schutz and what

contributions or what things you feel the best about that you've done since you've been here, or maybe some insights, observations, an anecdote, just something a little personal from your standpoint or from your vantage point.
For that many years, I know there's got to be bunches of them.
Well, yeah.
It's been a wonderful experience for me.
I've enjoyed it.
Well, in terms of what I've done, I think programmatically I'm proudest of establishing, or helping to establish, I didn't do it single-handedly, obviously, helping to establish
a sense of program for master's degrees and doctoral degrees, of requirements, of standards, of expectations.
I've embedded a number of courses since I've been here.
You mentioned just a couple.
Well, EDCI 675, which is Teaching Strategies and Patterns of Learning, is one.
Okay.
It was designed around the idea that we should use what we know about how people learn to design better ways to teach them.
The basic idea.
I did it as an outraged response to the educational psychologists with whom I worked at Stanford who didn't care about teaching.
They just said, learning is interesting all by itself.
And I said, but why do you make teachers learn about learning if you're not going to help them draw the connections?
And they said, that's their problem.
It's not our problem.
Then you belong in psych, I think, not in ed psych.
So I thought, boy, if I ever get the chance, I'm going to make a course that will do that.
And it's been successful since the first time I taught it.
I expected to have five people sign up for the first year.
I had 50.
The first time I offered it, it just bowled me over.
How long ago was that?
It was 1971, something like that.
And it's been taught ever since?
Usually twice a year.
Are you still teaching it?
I still teach it.
I'm teaching it right now.
I do it differently every time, but still, that's the same basic focus.
And John Denton shares that course with me every now and again.
He teaches it.
That's because I believe that no course should belong to somebody.
Because if it does, when that person goes, dies, retires, whatever, it's gone.
That's true.
If you really believe in the content and the curriculum, then you've got to have two or more people that are associated with it.
And I invented instructional theory.
And I invented curriculum theory.
And I invented curricular management theory.
Well, I've done an undergraduate course that was born, struggled, and died.
Well, those come about once in a while, too.

It was a good idea to try to help the undergraduate see that knowledge has a structure, and that when you learn your area of special secondary, you learn your teaching field, you need to learn its structure.
So that you can say to the students you teach, this is how what I'm teaching you fits into this field.
This is what you're going to study next, and after that, what you'll be able to do, and so on and so on.
And somebody who's got difficulties, well, you can analyze what they're missing in the structure.
You talked a little bit, or you have mentioned several different things that you do.
Can you give me just a brief overview?
You're very busy, and we talked a lot about time.
How do you balance your time as far as teaching and service type activities and research?
In the last few years since I came back from the Target 2000 project, well, when I was department head, I was mostly an administrator with some teaching
So you could say service and teaching.
Target 2000 was the same story.
So when I came back from Target 2000 in 1983, I was so far behind in everything that I had you to scramble.
I was hanging on by my fingernails as though I was legitimate as a teacher.
I crawled back.
I'm reasonably confident of what I'm doing now.
Between doing that, updating and upgrading my teaching, and taking care of all the doctoral people that I work with, there isn't an awful lot of time left.
And that's where I'm in trouble right now.
Is there pressure put on professors in this department or in any department
To publish or to write?
We're all expected to, all the time.
It is recognized that some will be more productive than others.
I have some things on my writing agenda that I have worked on and that I will continue to work on until I get them done and published.
But they're hard.
They're big papers.
They're nasty, conceptual.
And it requires lots of time.
It requires somebody to sit down and interact with periodically in order to do the job right.
And I said, there's a lot of time.
Well, we only have so many hours, and we just can't do everything we'd like to do.
But is there something that you would like to close with that kind of ties all the rules?
about all the different things we've talked about with the College of Education and the perceptions of the past, the present, the future?
Well, it seems to me that the major things that have happened are the tremendous growth in student body, which she's experienced and we have experienced.
That has meant a growth in faculty.
numbers and diversities, which has offered us wonderful opportunities to cross-fertilize.
If only we could ever find the time and the opportunity to take advantage of that.
I am rather, now, rather systematically trying to socialize with people in other departments and other, trying to do that.
At least
of letting them know that we're not boring.
And also with students.
I've started getting a lot of entertaining with graduate students, which I've enjoyed a lot.
When you say systematically, and I've had that feeling from a lot of teachers that they don't get to do that enough.
How do you systematically go about it?
Because everybody has to make a concentrated effort because it does not just happen because of the time constraints.
Well, you see, I'm in a somewhat unique position.
I'm in the process of a divorce, so I have no children now.
My children are grown, having children of their own.
So if I want to have somebody in for dinner on Tuesday night, I have nobody to consult but me.
So there's no family disruption that occurs as a result.
I normally confine my activity to the weekends, but occasionally, if there's a need for something, Tuesday night or Wednesday night.
No, you simply have to say to yourself, it's time to get out of the rut.
Quit seeing the same old people.
To some degree, that says you've got to take a little more risk.
You've got to invite somebody that you think is somewhat more prestigious than you are in the hierarchy of things.
And if they say no, why, you aren't going to be crushed by it.
So far, they've all said yes.
Maybe everybody's looking for somebody to start.
Somebody has to make that initial move.
Well, I like it.
I'm really having a lot of fun doing it.
As I get to know people there, a lot of the strangeness is cross-departmental operation resolved.
It's fun.
That's great.

So I think we can look for some interesting kinds of developments in the next few years, on a number of fronts, and hope that as the university evolves in its growth toward excellence, we will be a part of that.
I don't have time probably to go into this, but you kept mentioning or referencing the Target 2000.
Did you?
Were you?
I was the staff director of that.
For this college or for the?
For the whole system.
I didn't know that.
Two years.
That report.
Okay, great.
Dr. Schultz, thank you.
I really enjoyed it.
visiting with you and learning a little bit more about this department and your perceptions of what has gone on.
And I hope that you'll let me come back if I have a few added questions.
